'''''Mystery Fun House''''' is a text adventure game written by [[Scott Adams (game designer)|Scott Adams]], "Adventure 7" in the series released by [[Adventure International]].<ref name="Moby">{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/mystery-fun-house|title=Mystery Fun House|work=MobyGames|accessdate=2008-07-22}}</ref>  The player explores a [[fun house]] explore to locate a set of secret plans, solving puzzles along the way.<ref name="AMG">{{cite web|last=Scoleri III|first=Joseph|url=http://www.allgame.com/cg/agg.dll?p=agg&sql=1:23022|title=Adventure 7: Mystery Fun House|work=allgame|publisher=All Media Guide|accessdate=2008-07-22}}</ref> ''Mystery Fun House'' was produced in only one week<ref name="NA2">{{cite journal|last=Francis|first=Garry|date=July–August 1985|title=Behind the Scenes|journal=[[Page 6|New Atari User]]|issue=16|page=20|url=http://www.page6.org/archive/issue_16/page_20.htm|accessdate=2008-07-22}}</ref> and was among the most difficult games in the series.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Francis|first=Garry|date=July–August 1984|title=Scott Adams' Adventureland|journal=[[Page 6|New Atari User]]|issue=10|page=10|url=http://www.page6.org/archive/issue_10/page_10.htm|accessdate=2008-07-22}}</ref>

A [[ZX Spectrum]] version was planned but never released.<ref name="world of Spectrum">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0009988|title=Mystery Fun House|work=World of Spectrum|accessdate=2008-12-13}}</ref>

== Gameplay ==

Gameplay involves moving from location to location, picking up any objects found there, and using them somewhere else to unlock puzzles. Commands took the form of [[verb]] and [[noun]], e.g. "Take Wrench". Movement from location to location was limited to North, South, East, West, Up and Down.

The player of this game must navigate through a maze<ref name="Analog">{{cite journal|last=Griffin|first=Brad |date=March–April 1983|title=Scott Adams Adventures 1–12|journal=[[ANALOG Computing]]|issue=10|url=http://www.cyberroach.com/analog/an10/default.htm}}</ref> and a shooting gallery, charm a mermaid,<ref name="MicroA">{{cite magazine|last=Matthews|first=Ken|date=December 1984|title=Scott Adams' Classic Adventures: Mystery Funhouse|magazine=Micro Adventurer|publisher=Sunshine Publications|location=London|issue=14|page=19|url=https://archive.org/stream/micro-adventurer-14/Micro_Adventurer_Issue_14_1984_Dec#page/n17/mode/2up | accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> and turn off a steam [[calliope (music)|calliope]] that is so loud the player's instructions are misunderstood – a reference to the "Loud Room" in ''[[Zork I]]''.<ref name="Malinche">{{cite web|url=http://www.malinche.net/scottadamstextadventuregames.html|title=Scott Adams Text Adventure Games: Mystery Fun House|work=Malinche Entertainment|publisher=Malinche Entertainment Corp.|accessdate=2008-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530111401/http://www.malinche.net/scottadamstextadventuregames.html|archive-date=2008-05-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> In one room is a trampoline that the player can enter, deposit items, and then exit. The player can then carry the trampoline around, regardless of how much it is holding, thus extending one's carrying capacity indefinitely. Violent solutions to puzzles are discouraged by a gameplay feature which sees the [[player character]] ejected from the fun house by a bouncer whenever certain commands are typed.<ref name="Malinche" />

==Reception==
''[[Electronic Games]]'' in 1981 warned against beginners to adventure games playing ''Mystery Fun House'' because of the difficulty, but stated that for others it "should provide a rousing good time".<ref name="eg198101">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-premiere/Electronic_Games_Issue_01_Vol_01_01_1981_Winter_Premiere#page/n59/mode/2up | title=Computer Playland | work=Electronic Games | date=January 1981 | accessdate=28 January 2015 | pages=61}}</ref>

== Legacy ==
''Mystery Fun House'' was among a number of classic Scott Adams adventures made available for free download by non-profit gaming organisation Infinite Frontiers in 2003.<ref name="CVG">{{cite news|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=92409|title=Classic Scott Adams Adventures for free|last=Walkland|first=Nick|date=2003-06-12|work=Computer and Video Games|publisher=Future Publishing |accessdate=2008-07-22}}</ref> It was also included as part of [[magnussoft]]'s ''C64 Classix'' compilation for Windows and Mac CD-ROM.<ref name="Moby2">{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/c64-classix|title=C64 Classix|work=MobyGames|accessdate=2008-07-22}}</ref>

